# [IPPM](../wg/ippm.html)

## Summary

The IPPM working group held a joint session with the BMWG at IETF 126. The meeting covered progress updates on active working group drafts (Alternate Marking, encrypted PDMv2, STAMP ECN, and STAMP MPLS extensions) and presentations on several new benchmarking and performance measurement proposals. These proposals focused on power consumption, source address validation (SAV), RPKI relying party and route origin validation (ROV) behavior, AI fabric switching efficiency, and AI agent operations. 

The chairs noted that future meetings might operate under a newly proposed joint charter name, BPM (Benchmarking and Performance Measurement).

---

## Key Discussion Points

### 1. Welcome and Agenda Bashing
* **Presenter**: Marcus Ihlar
* **Slides**: [0. Chair Slides](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-ippm-sessb-0-chair-slides-02)
* **Discussion**: Marcus Ihlar reviewed IETF policies, administrative details, and the agenda. He noted that the group is currently discussing a joint charter proposal for IPPM and BMWG under a combined name (e.g., BPM). The agenda was approved as proposed.

### 2. Alternate Marking Deployment Framework & YANG Models
* **Presenter**: Giuseppe Fioccola
* **Drafts**: [draft-ietf-ippm-alt-mark-deployment](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-ippm-alt-mark-deployment/) and [draft-ietf-ippm-alt-mark-yang](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-ippm-alt-mark-yang/)
* **Discussion**:
  * **Deployment Framework**: Working Group Last Call (WGLC) has concluded. Revisions addressed comments from Benoit Claise, Alex Clemm, and Tim Chown. Key updates include distinguishing the base document from complementary work, clarifying on-node vs. centralized collector computation options (referencing RFC 9951/9947), and extending the controller domain definition to cover trust relationships.
  * **YANG Models**: The configuration model was refined to define profiles under interfaces. The configuration and telemetry models are separated.
  * **IPFIX Extension**: Refined to improve flow aggregation description and align naming conventions. 
  * **Next Steps**: Move the deployment draft forward. A joint WGLC for the IPFIX draft with the OPSAWG is planned.

### 3. IPv6 Performance and Diagnostic Metrics Version 2 (PDMv2)
* **Presenter**: Nalini Elkins
* **Draft**: [draft-ietf-ippm-encrypted-pdmv2](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-ippm-encrypted-pdmv2/)
* **Discussion**:
  * The draft has been revised to remove cryptographic key exchange and security context details from its core scope (suggesting a RADIUS EAP registration flow as an example instead). PDMv2 will focus strictly on the measurements, data structures, and packet contents.
  * PDMv2 operates at the IPv6 layer and needs a new option type allocation from IANA.
  * **Feedback**: Mohamed Boucadair and Thomas Graf suggested requesting early reviews from the Security, Internet, Operations, and Transport (TSVART) directorates.

### 4. Power Benchmarking
* **Presenter**: Shailesh
* **Discussion**:
  * Updates to the power benchmarking draft include adding strict laboratory environment conditions (temperature, humidity, atmospheric pressure) based on CES 203136.
  * The draft added a "typical power" test scenario and simplified traffic configurations by removing inter-packet delay.
  * **Feedback**: Giuseppe Fioccola and Shailesh noted that the draft needs reviews from energy efficiency experts (such as the Green WG) before advancing to WGLC.

### 5. Source Address Validation (SAV) Benchmarking Methodology
* **Presenter**: Linhui Sun
* **Discussion**:
  * Clarified intra-domain and inter-domain SAV scopes. Added terms like Limited Propagation Prefix (RPP) and Hidden Prefix (caused by Direct Server Return).
  * Test cases for Customer-Provider interfaces were refined, and the test reporting format was expanded.
  * Lan Chang noted that the cases align with SAVNET working group problem statement drafts.

### 6. MPLS In-situ OAM (IOAM)
* **Presenter**: Rakesh Gandhi
* **Discussion**:
  * Outlined the encapsulation of IOAM options in MPLS using MPLS Network Actions (MNA) in-stack and post-stack. Direct Export (DEX) is supported in both formats.
  * Thomas Graf encouraged the IPPM and BMWG communities to review the draft, as the MPLS working group is preparing for a WGLC.

### 7. STAMP Class of Service (CoS) Extension for ECN
* **Presenter**: Greg White
* **Draft**: [draft-ietf-ippm-stamp-cos-ecn](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-ippm-stamp-cos-ecn/)
* **Discussion**:
  * Revision 01 resolves reflector ECN signaling ambiguity by mandating "not ECT" (00) when a reflector cannot set the requested value.
  * Discussed an alternative "CoS v2" encoding proposal that includes explicit DSCP/ECN values for both forward and reverse paths. While this helps on-path observers, it breaks backward compatibility.
  * Giuseppe Fioccola suggested referencing hybrid/on-path measurements (such as [draft-ietf-ippm-on-path-active-measurements](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-ippm-on-path-active-measurements/)) to support hop-by-hop measurements.
  * Greg White invited implementations to collaborate on interop testing at the next Hackathon.

### 8. Performance Measurement (PM) Streaming and Collection
* **Presenter**: Bin Young
* **Discussion**:
  * This work was split from a single CCAMP document into three: two generic PM drafts for IPPM and one transport-specific draft remaining in CCAMP.
  * The generic IPPM drafts cover PM collection measurements (including counts, snapshots, and tri-marks based on ITU-T G.7710) and interval capability discovery.
  * **Feedback**: Thomas Graf proposed initiating a liaison check with ITU-T SG15. Giuseppe Fioccola suggested looking at tagging data based on measurement type (active/passive/hybrid). Chin suggested checking for overlap with NETCONF and LMAP YANG models.

### 9. RPKI Relying Party Benchmarking
* **Presenter**: Lan Chang
* **Discussion**:
  * Focuses on the functional correctness (e.g., certification path validation and syntax checking) of RPKI relying parties (RP), with performance as a secondary objective.
  * Presenters plan to add CRL processing tests and daemon mode operation evaluations in future versions.

### 10. STAMP Extensions for Reflecting MPLS Headers
* **Presenter**: Rakesh Gandhi
* **Draft**: [draft-ietf-ippm-stamp-ext-hdr](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-ippm-stamp-ext-hdr/)
* **Discussion**:
  * This draft mirrors the IPv6 extensions draft for MPLS data planes. Revisions aligned the draft with the IPv6 version (specifically on egress node behavior and header control sub-TLVs).
  * An open-source implementation is available. The authors requested working group adoption.

### 11. Residual Bit Error Rate (BER) using STAMP
* **Presenter**: Rakesh Gandhi
* **Discussion**:
  * Focuses on measuring bit errors escaping FEC/CRC using STAMP padding patterns. A new TLV was added to detect burst bit errors.
  * Both Cisco (experimental) and open-source implementations exist. 
  * **Feedback**: Richard Foot and Lichang supported early IANA code point allocation and adoption. Lichang suggested setting up a GitHub repository to track issues.

### 12. Route Origin Validation (ROV) Benchmarking for Routers
* **Presenter**: Linhui Sun
* **Discussion**:
  * Designed to measure the latency, scalability, and robustness of routers performing ROV.
  * Revisions based on SIDOPS mailing list feedback expanded the VRP dataset characteristics, clarified update state changes, and refined BGP convergence test cases.

### 13. AI Fabric Benchmarking / Switching Efficiency Framework
* **Presenter**: Wei Chang Sun / Student
* **Slides**: [AI Fabric Benchmarking Suite](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-ippm-ai-fabric-benchmarking-suite-00)
* **Discussion**:
  * Proposed a mathematical "switching efficiency" framework (eta) to evaluate how effectively AI network switching resources translate to computational progress in LLM training.
  * **Feedback**: Karsten noted that the draft reads like an academic paper rather than an IETF standard and raised concerns about potential AI-generated text in Section 5. Wei Chang Sun clarified that the goal is to define a high-level industry metric (similar to Power over Ethernet) that hardware vendors and operators can use to optimize network fabrics, and they intend to adapt the concepts into practical testing tools.

### 14. Lightning Talks (Proposed Work)
* **Packet Loss Monitoring Framework for List of Congestions**: An unidentified presenter summarized a framework to detect and isolate packet loss events in network devices without modifying packet headers.
* **Active Packet Loss Interpretation Considerations** (Presented by Linhui Sun, referencing *draft-liu-ippm-active-loss-considerations*): Proposes separating observed active measurement losses from inferred root causes (e.g., congestion, routing changes, or security filtering) using on-path telemetry context.
* **AI Agent Security Benchmark** (Presented by Mailington, referencing *draft-han-bmwg-agent-security-benchmark*): Outlined a 4-dimension framework (Foundation Model, Interaction, Operation, and Basic Security) to evaluate security risks in AI agent deployments.
* **AI Agents Benchmarking in Network Operations** (Presented by Luis): Outlined a methodology to evaluate AI agents executing operational tasks (e.g., troubleshooting and configuration) based on metrics like completion time, success rate, and token efficiency. Boris Khasanov (in chat) highlighted that this work should coordinate with the newly proposed Agent Protocols BoF/WG.

